Independent Auditor's Report
To the Plan Administrator of
The Consolidated Edison Retirement Plan
Opinion
We have audited the financial statements of The Consolidated Edison Retirement Plan (the "Plan"), an
employee benefit plan subject to the Employee Retirement Income Security Act of 1974 ("ERISA"),
which comprise the statements of net assets available for benefits and accumulated plan benefits as of
December 31, 2024 and 2023, and the related statements of changes in net assets available for
benefits and changes in accumulated plan benefits for the years then ended, and the related notes to
the financial statements.
In our opinion, the accompanying financial statements present fairly, in all material respects, the net
assets available for benefits and accumulated plan benefits of the Plan as of December 31, 2024 and
2023, and the changes in its net assets available for benefits and changes in accumulated plan benefits
for the years then ended, in accordance with accounting principles generally accepted in the United
States of America.
Basis for Opinion
We conducted our audits in accordance with auditing standards generally accepted in the United States
of America ("GAAS"). Our responsibilities under those standards are further described in the Auditor's
Responsibilities for the Audit of the Financial Statements section of our report. We are required to be
independent of the Plan and to meet our other ethical responsibilities, in accordance with the relevant
ethical requirements relating to our audits. We believe that the audit evidence we have obtained is
sufficient and appropriate to provide a basis for our audit opinion.
Responsibilities of Management for the Financial Statements
Management is responsible for the preparation and fair presentation of the financial statements in
accordance with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States of America, and for the
design, implementation, and maintenance of internal control relevant to the preparation and fair
presentation of financial statements that are free from material misstatement, whether due to fraud or
error.
In preparing the financial statements, management is required to evaluate whether there are conditions
or events, considered in the aggregate, that raise substantial doubt about the Plan's ability to continue
as a going concern for one year after the date that the financial statements are available to be issued.
Management is also responsible for maintaining a current Plan instrument, including all Plan
amendments, administering the Plan, and determining that the Plan's transactions that are presented
and disclosed in the financial statements are in conformity with the Plan's provisions, including
maintaining sufficient records with respect to each of the participants, to determine the benefits due or
which may become due to such participants.
1

Auditor's Responsibilities for the Audit of the Financial Statements
Our objectives are to obtain reasonable assurance about whether the financial statements as a whole
are free from material misstatement, whether due to fraud or error, and to issue an auditor's report that
includes our opinion. Reasonable assurance is a high level of assurance but is not absolute assurance
and therefore is not a guarantee that an audit conducted in accordance with GAAS will always detect a
material misstatement when it exists. The risk of not detecting a material misstatement resulting from
fraud is higher than for one resulting from error, as fraud may involve collusion, forgery, intentional
omissions, misrepresentations, or the override of internal control. Misstatements are considered
material if there is a substantial likelihood that, individually or in the aggregate, they would influence the
judgment made by a reasonable user based on the financial statements.
In performing an audit in accordance with GAAS, we:
 Exercise professional judgment and maintain professional skepticism throughout the audit.
 Identify and assess the risks of material misstatement of the financial statements, whether due
to fraud or error, and design and perform audit procedures responsive to those risks. Such
procedures include examining, on a test basis, evidence regarding the amounts and disclosures
in the financial statements.
 Obtain an understanding of internal control relevant to the audit in order to design audit
procedures that are appropriate in the circumstances, but not for the purpose of expressing an
opinion on the effectiveness of the Plan's internal control. Accordingly, no such opinion is
expressed.
 Evaluate the appropriateness of accounting policies used and the reasonableness of significant
accounting estimates made by management, as well as evaluate the overall presentation of the
financial statements.
 Conclude whether, in our judgment, there are conditions or events, considered in the aggregate,
that raise substantial doubt about the Plan's ability to continue as a going concern for a
reasonable period of time.
We are required to communicate with those charged with governance regarding, among other matters,
the planned scope and timing of the audit, significant audit findings, and certain internal control-related
matters that we identified during the audit.
Supplemental Schedules Required by ERISA

The Consolidated Edison Retirement Plan
Notes to Financial Statements
1. Description of the Plan
The following description of The Consolidated Edison Retirement Plan (the “Retirement Plan”)
provides only general information. Participants should refer to the Retirement Plan document for
a more complete description of the Retirement Plan's provisions.
General
The Retirement Plan is a defined benefit, noncontributory pension plan sponsored by
Consolidated Edison Company of New York, Inc. (the “Plan Sponsor” or “CECONY”) and is
designed to comply with the Employee Retirement Income Security Act of 1974, as amended
(“ERISA”). CECONY is a subsidiary of Consolidated Edison, Inc. (“CEI” or the “Company”).
The Retirement Plan covers the following groups of persons:
1. each Orange and Rockland Utilities, Inc. (“O&R”) management employee who was hired
before January 1, 2017;
2. each O&R hourly employee who was hired before June 1, 2014;
3. each CECONY management employee who was hired before January 1, 2017;
4. each CECONY weekly employee who is represented by the International Brotherhood of
Electrical Workers, AFL-CIO, Local 3, and hired on or before June 25, 2017;
5. each CECONY weekly employee who is represented by the Utility Workers Union of
America, AFL-CIO, Local 1-2, who is covered under the cash balance pension formula and
given a Pension Choice, as defined below, who elects to remain in the Retirement Plan;
6. each CECONY and O&R employee who is covered under the cash balance pension formula
and elected to remain in the Retirement Plan when given a Pension Choice;
7. each eligible employee of Consolidated Edison Energy Massachusetts, Inc. (“CEEMI”), also
known as “WEMCO”; and
8. each employee who transferred directly from CECONY or O&R to another CEI affiliate.
Assets of the Retirement Plan are held in the Consolidated Edison Pension Plan Master Trust (the
“Pension Trust”) administered by BNY Mellon. The designated investment managers manage
the assets of the Pension Trust allocated in accordance with the investment policy approved by
the Named Fiduciary Committee. A committee of the Board of Directors of CEI and the Board of
Trustees of CECONY (together the “Boards”) approve the funding policy and employer
contributions to the Retirement Plan. Each participating employer contributes to the Retirement
Plan on behalf of its participating employees and shares in the expenses, on a pro-rata basis, of
the Retirement Plan.
Benefits and Vesting
The Retirement Plan operates in accordance with separate and distinct benefit formulas:
1. two benefit formulas for CECONY management employees hired before January 1, 1983
and/or January 1, 2001;
2. two benefit formulas for CECONY Local 1-2 weekly employees hired before July 1, 2012
and CECONY Local 3 weekly employees hired before January 1, 2010 negotiated in
collective bargaining agreements;
3. one benefit formulas for O&R management employees hired before January 1, 2001;
4. one benefit formula for O&R hourly employees (Local 503) hired prior to January 1, 2010
and negotiated in collective bargaining agreements;

5. the cash balance formula that is effective for (i) each management employee hired by
CECONY or O&R on and after January 1, 2001 and before January 1, 2017, (ii) each
employee of CEEMI and CED Operating Company, L.P. ("CEDOC"); (iii) each Local 3-
IBEW or O&R Local 503-IBEW employee hired on or after January 1, 2010 and before June
25, 2017 for Local 3-IBEW; and (iv) each Local l-2 employee hired on or after July 1, 2012;
6. members of O&R Local 503-IBEW hired between January 1, 2010 and June 1, 2014, who
are covered under the cash balance formula had, up to December 31, 2015, an opportunity to
cease participation in the Retirement Plan and begin participation in the newly created
defined contribution pension formula in the Consolidated Edison Thrift Savings Plan
(referred to as a “Pension Choice”). A second opportunity to do this was made available from
July 1, 2020 to May 31, 2023. Members of O&R Local 503-IBEW hired before June 1, 2014,
who did not exercise their Pension Choice election remain covered under the cash balance
formula in the Retirement Plan. Members have a choice to begin participation in the defined
contribution pension formula in the Consolidated Edison Thrift Savings Plan beginning with
the first quarter following their choice election. Members of O&R Local 503-IBEW, hired
after June 1, 2014, are not eligible to participate in the Retirement Plan;
7. members of CECONY Local 3-IBEW hired before June 30, 2013 who are covered under the
cash balance formula had, up to December 31, 2015, an opportunity to elect “Pension
Choice,” as described in subsection (6) immediately above. Members of CECONY Local 3-
IBEW hired before June 25, 2017 who did not exercise their Pension Choice election remain
covered under the cash balance formula in the Retirement Plan;
8. members of CECONY Local 1-2 hired between July 1, 2012 and June 25, 2016 who are
covered under the cash balance formula had, up to June 20, 2020, an opportunity to elect
“Pension Choice”. Members of CECONY Local 1-2 hired between July 1, 2012 and June 25,
2016 who did not exercise their Pension Choice election remain covered under the cash
balance formula in the Retirement Plan;
9. effective June 1, 2017, all CECONY management employees covered under the Final
Average Pay pension formula, regardless of points at retirement, or O&R management
employees covered under the Career Average Pay pension formulas will have the option to
choose a lump-sum payment upon retirement, in addition to the existing monthly payment
option. Additionally, for all participants under the cash balance pension formula, the option
to enroll in “Pension Choice” was available and could have been selected between June 1,
2017 and December 31, 2021;
10.effective January 1, 2020, Local 503 employees covered under the Career Average Pay
pension formula will have the option to choose a lump-sum payment upon retirement; and
11.effective January 1, 2022, Local 3 employees covered under the Final Average Pay pension
formula will have the option to choose a lump-sum payment upon retirement.
The cash balance formula in the Retirement Plan provides benefits based on an employee's
quarterly salary level, the portion of the employee’s annual salary in excess of the Social
Security wage base, and a point system based on the aggregate of the employee’s years of
accredited service and age. The cash balance pension formula provides a quarterly salary or
compensation credit, from 4% to 7%, and provides a return on a participant’s cumulative pension
benefit from a minimum 3% to a maximum 9% annually. Local 503 participants in the Cash
Balance Plan who elected to be covered under the defined contribution formula in the Thrift
Savings Plan (Pension Choice) will have a minimum return of 4% on their Cash Balance
account.

The Consolidated Edison Retirement Plan
Notes to Financial Statements
In general, employees become vested in the Retirement Plan upon completing three to five years
of vesting service. The Retirement Plan pays pension benefits in various forms depending upon
which group and benefit formula covers the participant. Normal retirement age is 65 and early
retirement is available to certain participants under the traditional defined benefit plan formula
who meet specific age and service requirements. As mandated by the Retirement Equity Act of
1984, the Retirement Plan also pays benefits to surviving spouses of vested participants.
Assets Held for the 401(h)
As permitted by Section 401(h) of the Internal Revenue Code (the “Code”), the Retirement Plan
includes a Retiree Health Program (the “Program”) component, which is intended to provide
medical, hospital, prescription drug and vision care benefits to certain retired employees of
CECONY, their dependents and surviving spouses. The net assets held for the 401(h) are
calculated based on a pro-rata percentage allocation of the net assets in the Retirement Plan. The
total investment income attributed to the 401(h) is calculated based on the income attributable to
the allocated 401(h) assets, and the net appreciation/(depreciation) on those assets, which is
based on a pro-rata percentage allocation of the realized and unrealized gains/losses of the assets
in the Retirement Plan.
In accordance with Section 401(h) of the Code, the Retirement Plan's investments for the 401(h)
may not be used for, or diverted to, any purposes other than providing health benefits for retirees
of CECONY and their dependents and surviving spouses. The related obligations for health
benefits are not included in the Retirement Plan’s obligations in the Statements of Accumulated
Plan Benefits but are reflected as obligations in the financial statements of the Program.
Retirement Plan participants do not contribute to the 401(h). Employer contributions or qualified
transfers to the 401(h) are determined annually and are at the discretion of the Plan Sponsor. The
401(h) does not provide benefits to O&R participants or to employees of other CEI affiliates.
Allocation of the Pension Trust
The dollar and share amounts included in the following footnote disclosures represent the total
amounts for the Pension Trust, which includes amounts that are allocated to the 401(h), unless
otherwise specified.
2. Summary of Significant Accounting Policies
The following are the significant accounting policies followed by the Retirement Plan:
Basis of Accounting
The accompanying financial statements are prepared on the accrual basis of accounting in
accordance with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States of America.
Use of Estimates
The preparation of financial statements in conformity with accounting principles generally
accepted in the United States of America requires management to make estimates and
assumptions that affect the reported amounts of assets, liabilities and changes therein, disclosure
of contingent assets and liabilities, and the actuarial present value of accumulated plan benefits at
the date of the financial statements and the reported amounts of revenues and expenses during
the reporting period. Actual results could differ from those estimates.
10

The Consolidated Edison Retirement Plan
Notes to Financial Statements
Valuation Policy
Investments are reported at fair value. Fair value is the price that would be received to sell an
asset or paid to transfer a liability in an orderly transaction between market participants at the
measurement date. The Retirement Plan’s valuation policies and procedures are approved by
management of the Plan Sponsor. See Note 11 for discussion of fair value measurements.
Investment Transactions and Related Investment Income
The net appreciation in the fair value of investments consists of the realized gains or losses and
the net change in unrealized appreciation on those investments.
Dividends are recorded on the ex-dividend date, and interest income and expenses are recorded
on the accrual basis. Interest income includes accretion of market discounts and original issue
discounts and amortization of premiums. Market discounts and original issue discounts are
accreted to income over the life of the underlying investment using the effective interest method.
All security transactions are recorded on the trade date. Premiums and discounts on debt
securities are amortized to maturity. Gains or (losses) on sales of securities are based on average
cost.
Translation of Foreign Assets and Liabilities
The accounting records of the Retirement Plan are maintained in U.S. Dollars. Assets and
liabilities denominated in foreign currencies are translated at period end rates of exchange with
the resulting unrealized gains and (losses) reflected in the Statements of Changes in Net Assets
Available for Benefits. Purchases and sales of securities and income receipts and expense
payments are translated into U.S. Dollars at the prevailing exchange rate on the respective dates
of the transactions.
Net realized gains and (losses) on foreign currency transactions represent net gains and (losses)
from sales and maturities of foreign currency forward contracts, disposition of foreign
currencies, the difference between the amount of net investment income accrued and the U.S.
Dollar amount actually received, and gains and (losses) between trade and settlement date on
purchases and sales of securities and are reflected in the Statements of Changes in Net Assets
Available for Benefits.
Subsequent Events
The Retirement Plan has evaluated subsequent events through October 8, 2025, which is the date
the financial statements were available to be issued.
3. Transactions with Parties-in-Interest
Certain plan assets are invested in money market funds managed by BNY Mellon Investment
Adviser, Inc., an affiliate of BNY Mellon, and therefore transactions in such investments qualify
as party-in-interest transactions which are exempt from ERISA's prohibited transaction rules.
BNY Mellon also manages securities lending transactions of the Pension Trust that qualify as
party-in-interest transactions and receives fees for such services.
Fees paid by the Pension Trust to BNY Mellon and State Street for securities lending amounted
to $79,558 and $69,786 for the years ended December 31, 2024 and 2023, respectively; see Note

4. Risks and Uncertainties
The Retirement Plan invests in various investment securities. Investment securities are exposed
to various risks such as interest rate, market and credit risks. Due to the level of risk associated
with certain investment securities, it is at least reasonably possible that changes in the values of
investment securities will occur in the near term and that such changes could materially affect the
amounts reported in the Statements of Net Assets Available for Benefits.
Retirement Plan contributions are made and the actuarial present value of accumulated plan
benefits are reported based on certain assumptions pertaining to interest rates, inflation rates and
employee demographics, all of which are subject to change. Due to uncertainties inherent in the
estimations and assumptions process, it is at least reasonably possible that changes in these
estimates and assumptions in the near term would be material to the financial statements.
5. Administration Expenses
Administrative expenses, including investment management and actuarial fees, are paid through
the Pension Trust by the Retirement Plan. If, in accordance with the applicable law, the expenses
cannot be paid out of the Pension Trust fund, such expenses will be paid by the participating
employers.
6. Funding Policy
The Plan Sponsor’s funding policy is to contribute the actuarial determined accounting cost of
the pension benefits, subject to statutory maximum and minimum Internal Revenue Service
(“IRS”) limits. The Company totaled $518,246 and $0 to the Retirement Plan during 2024 and
2023, respectively. The Company is in compliance with the minimum funding requirements of
the Retirement Plan.
The Plan Sponsor's funding policy with regard to the Program is to contribute the actuarial
determined accounting cost to the extent allowed by federal tax laws. During 2024, CECONY
contributed $4,900,000 to the 401(h) for retiree health benefits and $13,400,000 in 2023.
7. Plan Termination
Although it has not expressed any intention to do so, the Plan Sponsor has reserved the right to
amend or terminate the Retirement Plan subject to the provisions set forth in ERISA.
Under the provisions of ERISA, the Retirement Plan is insured by the Pension Benefit Guaranty
Corporation (“PBGC”) which would provide payments to participants, up to certain limits,
should unfunded vested benefits exist upon termination of the Retirement Plan.
Should the Retirement Plan terminate at some future time, its net assets generally will not be
available to provide participants’ benefits. Whether a particular participant’s accumulated plan
benefits will be paid depends on both the priority of those benefits and the level of benefits
12

The Consolidated Edison Retirement Plan
Notes to Financial Statements
guaranteed by the PBGC at that time. Some benefits may be fully or partially provided for by the
then existing assets and the PBGC guaranty while other benefits may not be provided for at all.
Generally, the PBGC guarantees most vested normal age retirement benefits, early retirement
benefits and certain disability and survivors’ pensions. However, the PBGC does not guarantee
all types of benefits under the Retirement Plan, and the amount of benefit protection is subject to
certain limitations. Vested benefits under the Retirement Plan are guaranteed at the level in effect
on the date of the Retirement Plan's termination. However, there is a statutory ceiling, which is
adjusted periodically, on the amount of an individual's monthly benefit that the PBGC
guarantees.
Whether all participants receive their benefits will depend on the sufficiency, at that time, of the
Retirement Plan's net assets to provide for accumulated benefit obligations and may also depend
on the financial condition of the Plan Sponsor and the level of benefits guaranteed by the PBGC.
Retiree Health Program Termination
The Retiree Health Program benefits are not guaranteed by the PBGC. The Plan Sponsor has
reserved the right to amend or terminate the Program. If the Program was terminated, all assets
allocated to the 401(h) would be applied to payment of liabilities under the Program. If a surplus
exists in the 401(h) after full satisfaction of all liabilities, the entire surplus would be paid by the
trustee to CECONY.
8. Securities Lending
The Retirement Plan enters into a securities lending program with the trustee, in its corporate
capacity as a lending agent. The program allows the trustee to loan securities, which are assets of
the Retirement Plan, to approved brokers (the "Borrowers"). The trustee requires Borrowers,
pursuant to a security loan agreement, to deliver collateral to secure each loan. The collateral is
required to equal at least 102 percent of the fair value of U.S. securities borrowed and 105
percent for non-U.S. securities borrowed. The Retirement Plan bears the risk of loss with respect
to the unfavorable change in fair value of the invested cash collateral. However, the Borrower
bears the risk of loss related to the decrease in the fair value of the securities’ collateral and,
therefore, will have to deliver additional cash securities to maintain the required collateral. In the
event of default by the Borrowers, the trustee shall indemnify the Retirement Plan by purchasing
replacement securities equal to the number of unreturned loaned securities or, if replacement
securities are not able to be purchased, the trustee shall credit the Retirement Plan for the market
value of the unreturned securities. In each case, the trustee would apply the proceeds from the
collateral for such a loan to make the Retirement Plan whole.

9. Accumulated Plan Benefits
Accumulated plan benefits represent the future benefit payments based on the Retirement Plan
provisions earned by all active, retired and vested terminated participants up to the date of the
valuation.
The actuarial present value of the accumulated plan benefits is the amount as of the valuation
date, as determined by the Retirement Plan’s independent actuary, giving recognition to such
factors as estimated deaths, participant terminations and retirements, time value of money
(through discounts for interest), and the effect of any Retirement Plan amendments on benefits.
The discount rate used to determine the benefit obligations at December 31, 2024 and 2023 was
6.75%. According to guidance provided by Financial Accounting Standards Board (“FASB”)
Accounting Standards Codification (“ASC”) 960, Plan Accounting – Defined Benefit Pension
Plans, assumed rates of return shall reflect the expected rates of return during the periods for
which payment of benefits is deferred and shall be consistent with returns realistically achievable
on the types of assets held by the Retirement Plan and the Retirement Plan’s investment policy.
The average expected retirement age is 62 for 2024 and 2023.
Changes in economic assumptions during the years ended December 31, 2024 and 2023 are
shown on the Statements of Changes in Accumulated Plan Benefits as changes in actuarial
assumptions.
The mortality assumption used to value the Retirement Plan liability was based on the Pri-2012
Total Dataset Tables in 2024 and 2023, as adjusted based on actual Company experience. The
mortality improvement scale used was MP-2021 for 2024 and 2023.
At December 31, 2024 and 2023, the actuarial assumption for inflation that was used to project
cost-of-living adjustments was 2.30% and 2.20%, respectively.
The foregoing actuarial assumptions are based on the presumption that the Retirement Plan will
continue. If the Retirement Plan were to terminate, different actuarial assumptions and other
factors might be applicable in determining the actuarial present value of accumulated plan
benefits.

11.Fair Value Measurements
FASB ASC 820, Fair Value Measurements and Disclosures, provides the framework for
measuring fair value. That framework provides a fair value hierarchy that prioritizes the inputs to
valuation techniques used to measure fair value. The hierarchy gives the highest priority to
unadjusted quoted prices in active markets for identical assets or liabilities (Level 1
measurements) and the lowest priority to unobservable inputs (Level 3 measurements). The three
levels of the fair value hierarchy under FASB ASC 820 are described as follows:
• Level 1 – Inputs to the valuation methodology are unadjusted quoted prices for identical assets
or liabilities in active markets that the plan has the ability to access.
15

The Consolidated Edison Retirement Plan
Notes to Financial Statements
• Level 2 – Inputs to the valuation methodology include:
◦ quoted prices for similar assets or liabilities in active markets;
◦ quoted prices for identical or similar assets or liabilities in inactive markets;
◦ inputs other than quoted prices that are observable for the asset or liability; and
◦ inputs that are derived principally from or corroborated by observable market data by
correlation or other means.
If the asset or liability has a specified (contractual) term, the Level 2 input must be
observable for substantially the full term of the asset or liability.
• Level 3 – Inputs to the valuation methodology are unobservable and significant to the fair
value measurement.
The asset or liability's fair value measurement level within the fair value hierarchy is based on
the lowest priority of any input that is significant to the fair value measurement. Valuation
techniques used need to maximize the use of observable inputs and minimize the use of
unobservable inputs.
Following is a description of the valuation methodologies used for assets and liabilities at fair
value:
Investments measured at net asset value (“NAV”): common/collective real estate trusts, private
equity funds, and hedge funds are valued at their last reported NAV. The NAV of the common/
collective trusts, private equity funds, and hedge funds, as provided by the trustee, is used as a
practical expedient to estimate fair value. The NAV is based on the fair value of the underlying
investments held by the fund less its liabilities.
Common stock and exchange traded funds: securities listed on any U.S. or non-U.S. stock
exchange or on the U.S. Nasdaq National Market ("NASDAQ") are valued at the last sale price
on the exchange or system in which they are principally traded, on the valuation date; if there is
no sale on the valuation date, securities are valued at the closing bid price or in the case of
securities sold, not yet purchased, are valued at the closing ask price.
Corporate, government and agency securities: valued on the basis of dealer-supplied bid
quotations or by using a pricing service selected by the Retirement Plan's trustees.
Exchange traded options and futures contracts: valued at the last sale price (or, if there is no sale
on the valuation day, bid price) in the market where such contracts are principally traded.
Short-term investments: valued at amortized cost, which approximates fair value.
Foreign currency: valued from quotes provided from a pricing service.
All other securities and assets for which market quotations are not readily available or for which
the above valuation procedures are deemed not to reflect fair value are valued in a manner that is
intended to reflect their fair value as determined in accordance with procedures approved by
management of the Plan Sponsor.

12.Derivatives
The Pension Trust enters into derivative instruments such as Forward Foreign Currency
Contracts and Futures Contracts to gain exposure to a market more rapidly or less expensively
than could be accomplished through the use of the cash markets. The Pension Trust, subject to
investment guidelines for current investment managers, can use exchange traded investment
instruments such as equity and interest rate futures, options on futures, over-the-counter (“OTC”)
options and forward exchange contracts. Select major financial institutions are used in derivative
transactions. When engaging in OTC and forward exchange contracts, there is exposure to credit
loss in the event of nonperformance by the counterparties to these transactions. This exposure is
managed through credit approvals, limits, monitoring procedures and, to the extent possible, by
restricting the period over which unpaid balances are allowed to accumulate. The investment
managers choose the brokers and also monitor and report market and counterparty credit risks
associated with the managers’ decision to trade derivatives. The Pension Trust does not
anticipate nonperformance by counterparties to these contracts; however, there can be no
assurance that the investment managers will be able to implement their credit guidelines or that
their risk monitoring strategies will be successful. No material loss would be expected from any
such nonperformance. Derivative instruments are recognized as either assets or liabilities in the
Statements of Net Assets Available for Benefits and are recorded at fair value (see Note 11, Fair
Value Measurements). While certain of the derivative activities may possess the substance of an
economic hedge, the Pension Trust does not hold derivative instruments that, pursuant to
accounting standards, are accounted for as hedging instruments.
The Retirement Plan reflects its portion of the fair value of derivatives as separate captions on
the Statements of Net Assets Available for Benefits.

Forward Foreign Currency Exchange Contracts
A forward foreign currency exchange contract ("forward currency contract") is a commitment to
purchase or sell a foreign currency at a future settlement date and at a negotiated rate. Forward
currency contracts are utilized to hedge a portion of the currency exposure that results from the
Pension Trust’s holdings of equity and fixed income securities denominated in foreign
currencies. Forward currency contracts are marked-to-market at the prevailing forward exchange
rate of the underlying currencies and the difference between contract value and market value is
recorded as unrealized appreciation/(depreciation) in the Pension Trust’s net assets. When the
forward currency contract is closed, the Pension Trust transfers the unrealized appreciation/
(depreciation) to a realized gain/(loss) equal to the change in the value of the forward currency
contract when it was opened and the value at the time it was closed or offset. Sales and purchases
of forward currency contracts having the same settlement date and broker, are offset, and any
gain/(loss) is realized on the date of offset.
Certain risks may arise upon entering into a forward currency contract from the potential
inability of counterparties to meet the terms of their contracts. Additionally, when utilizing
forward currency contracts to hedge, the Retirement Plan gives up the opportunity to profit from
favorable exchange rate movements during the term of the contract.

Futures Contracts
A futures contract is a contractual agreement to make or take delivery of a standardized quantity
of a specified grade or type of commodity or financial instrument at a specified future date in
accordance with terms specified by a regulated futures exchange. The Pension Trust uses equity
index and fixed income futures contracts to manage exposure to the market. Buying futures
contracts tends to increase the Pension Trust’s exposure to the underlying instrument. Selling
futures contracts tends to decrease the Pension Trust's exposure to the underlying instrument
held. Futures contracts are valued at the last settlement price at the end of each day on the
exchange upon which they are traded. Upon entering into a futures contract, the Pension Trust is
required to deposit cash equal to a certain percentage of the nominal value of the contract.
Pursuant to the futures contract, the Pension Trust agrees to receive from, or pay to, the broker an
amount of cash equal to the daily fluctuation in the value of the futures contract. Such receipts or
payments are known as "variation margin," which are settled daily and are included in the
realized gains/(losses) on futures contracts. The Pension Trust will record a variation margin

receivable or payable in the net assets for variation margins which have not yet been paid at the
end of the year. As of December 31, 2024 and 2023, a margin variation receivable of $7,561,732
and $24,958,561, respectively, was included in receivable from securities sold and a margin
variation payable of $(12,024,076) and $(6,508,520), respectively, was included in securities
purchased payable.
Futures contracts involve, to varying degrees, credit and market risks. The Pension Trust enters
into futures contracts on exchanges where the exchange acts as the counterparty to the
transaction. Thus, credit risk on such transactions is limited to the failure of the exchange. The
daily settlement on the futures contracts serves to greatly reduce credit risk. Losses in value may
arise from changes in the value of the underlying instrument or if there is an illiquid secondary
market for the contracts. In addition, there is the risk that there may not be an exact correlation
between a futures contract and the underlying index or security.

15.Tax Status
The IRS has determined and informed the Plan Sponsor, by a letter dated October 16, 2017, that
the Retirement Plan and related trust are designed in accordance with applicable sections of the
Code. The Retirement Plan has been amended since receiving the determination letter; however,
the Company believes that the Retirement Plan is designed and is currently being operated in
compliance with the applicable requirements of the Code. Accounting principles generally
accepted in the United States of America require management of the Plan Sponsor to evaluate tax
positions taken by the Retirement Plan and recognize a tax liability if the Retirement Plan has
taken an uncertain position that more likely than not would not be sustained upon examination
by the IRS. The Retirement Plan is subject to routine audits by taxing jurisdictions; however,
there are currently no audits for any tax periods in progress. Management of the Plan Sponsor
believes it is no longer subject to income tax examinations for the years ended prior to 2021.

Demographic and Other Assumptions
Inclusion date The valuation date coincident with or next following the date on which
the employee becomes a participant begins to earn benefit service.
New or rehired employees It was assumed there will be no new or rehired employees.
Benefit commencement
dates
• Deferred vested benefit It is assumed that current and future deferred vested participants elect
to defer payment of their annuity benefit until age 60 (age 62 for O&R).
• Deferred vested lump It is assumed that 50% of Con Edison participants who terminate
sums employment with less than 75 points take immediate lump sum cash
outs and 50% elect to defer payment of their benefit until age 60. It is
assumed that 33% of Con Edison traditional formula Management
participants over age 55 who terminate employment with more than 75
points take immediate lump sum cash outs and 67% elect to defer
payment of their benefit until age 60 (for those under age 55 with more
than 75 points, 11.55% assumed to take immediate lump sum cash
outs, 23.45% elect immediate benefit and 65% elect to defer their
benefit until age 55).
It is assumed that 50% of O&R traditional formula Management
participants (and for O&R union participants after December 31, 2019)
who terminate employment take lump sums upon eligibility for early
retirement and 50% elect to defer payment of their benefit until age 62.
It is assumed that 50% of participants under the cash balance benefit
formula take an immediate lump sum cash out equal to the cash
balance account, and 50% of participants defer the lump sum cash out
to age 62 for O&R groups and age 60 for all other groups.

• Disability benefit For CECONY Management, it is assumed that 90% of all disabled
participants elect to receive immediate payment of their benefit from the Plan
and 10% elect to defer payment of their benefit until age 60.
For CECONY Weekly, it is assumed that 90% of all disabled participants elect
to receive immediate payment of their benefit from the Plan and 10% elect to
defer payment of their benefit until age 60.
For CEI participants, it is assumed that all vested disabled participants elect
to receive immediate payment of their
cash balance accounts.
For O&R Management participants, it is assumed that all disabled participants
receive LTD benefits and continue to accrue pension benefits until age 65.
O&R Union participants who are disabled can either receive an immediate
pension benefit if they have met the eligibility requirements for disability
retirement or receive long-term disability (LTD) benefits and continue to
accrue pension benefits while on LTD. Currently, assumptions are made for
participants who are disabled prior to age 65 with regard to the LTD period.
The LTD
period assumed for those disabled prior to age 62 equals the lesser of (a) a
maximum period provided by the LTD Plan or (b) two years. Those disabled
at or after age 62 are assumed to receive LTD benefits and continue to
accrue benefits until age 65. The type of retirement benefit received after LTD
ceases depends on the
participant’s vesting and accredited service at the time LTD ceases.

contributions
Funding policy The Company’s funding policy is to contribute the current year
accounting cost as long as it is at least equal to the minimum required
contribution for the prior year.
Methods
Valuation date First day of plan year (January 1)
Funding target Present value of accrued benefits as required by regulations under
IRC §430.
Target normal cost Present value of benefits expected to accrue during the plan year
plus plan-related expenses expected to be paid from plan assets
during the plan year as required by regulations under IRC §430.
Decrement timing The approach used is called rounded middle of year (rounded MOY)
decrement timing. Most events are assumed to occur at the middle of
year during which the eligibility condition will be met or the start/end
date will occur. For death and disability decrements, the rate applied
is based on the participant’s rounded age (nearest integer age) at the
beginning of the year, to align with the methodology generally used to
create those rate tables. For retirement and withdrawal decrements:
the age is generally the participant’s rounded age at the middle of the
year.

Actuarial value of assets Average of the fair market value of assets on the valuation date and
12 and 24 months preceding the valuation date, adjusted for
contributions, benefits, administrative expenses and expected
earnings (with such expected earnings limited as described in IRS
Notice 2009-22). The average asset value must be within 10% of
market value, including discounted contributions receivable
(discounted using the effective interest rate for the prior plan year.)
The method of computing the actuarial value of assets complies with
rules governing the calculation of such values under the Pension
Protection Act of 2006 (PPA). These rules produce smoothed values
that reflect the underlying market value of plan assets but fluctuate
less than the market value. As a result, the actuarial value of assets
will be lower than the market value in some years and greater in other
years. However, over the long term under PPA’s smoothing rules,
the method has a significant bias to produce an actuarial value of
assets that is below the market value of assets.
The expected return used in this asset development is 7.0 % during
2022 and 6.75% during 2023. This return is limited each year to the
3rd segment rate.
Benefits not valued All benefits described in the Plan Provisions section of this report
were valued. WTW has reviewed the plan provisions with the plan
sponsor and, based on that review, is not aware of any significant
benefits required to be valued that were not.

Summary of Plan Provisions
Summary of Main Plan Provisions for CECONY Participants
Plan Provisions
The Consolidated Edison Retirement Plan for Management Employees (“Management Plan”) became
effective on January 1, 1983. The Consolidated Edison Pension and Benefits Plan (“Weekly Plan”)
became effective on August 1, 1975. Effective January 1, 2001, the two Con Edison pension plans were
merged together with the Employees’ Retirement Plan of Orange and Rockland Utilities, Inc. (O&R Plan)
and became The Consolidated Edison Retirement Plan.
A restated plan document was submitted to the IRS in January 2017. The restated plan document reflects
all changes reflected in the January 1, 2016 valuation, and includes the following changes adopted since
January 1, 2016:

Cost of Living Adjustment
Pension benefits are adjusted in April of each year by 75% of the percentage increase in the Consumer
Price Index (CPI-U) for the 12 months ended December 31 of the preceding year, subject to a maximum
annual adjustment of 3%. Members of Local 3 who are hired on or after June 26, 2005 are not entitled to
an automatic cost-of-living adjustment.
Pensioners’ Increase
Pensioners and beneficiaries in receipt whose monthly benefits as of March 2001 are less than $1,000
receive a $50 per month increase in benefits effective April 1, 2001.
Special Plan Provisions for former WMECo Employees
Effective May 2008, the Company sold its CEEMI operations. All benefits were frozen as of that date, but
participants remain eligible for retirement and deferred vested benefits. Benefits for former employees of
Western Massachusetts Electric Company (WMECo), which became part of Consolidated Edison Energy
Massachusetts, Inc., are calculated under their prior plan formula. The Con Edison plan pays the excess
of the total benefit calculated as if the individual was still covered under WMECo’s plan over the amount
paid by WMECo. The Con Edison plan is responsible for the growth in final average earnings and a
portion of the grow-in for the early retirement subsidy on the portion of the benefit accrued at WMECo, as
well as for future accruals. Employees hired at WMECo on or after January 1, 2000 are covered under
the cash balance benefit structure summarized in the section “Summary of Plan Provisions for CEI
Participants”. The key provisions of the WMECo benefits are as follows:
“Compensation” is a participant’s actual regular earnings plus shift differentials, Sunday
premium pay, on-call pay, overtime earnings (computed at straight-time rates) and bonuses or
incentive pay under a broadly available incentive pay program.
“Covered Compensation” is the average of the Social Security Taxable Wage Bases in effect
for each calendar year during the 35-year period ending with the last day of the calendar year
in which the participant attains Social Security Retirement Age.
“Final average earnings” is the highest average annual compensation earned for credited
service during any 60 consecutive months.

Plan Provisions
The Employees' Retirement Plan of Orange and Rockland Utilities, Inc. (O&R Plan) became effective
February 1, 1954. Effective January 1, 2001, the two Con Edison pension plans were merged together
with the O&R Plan and became The Consolidated Edison Retirement Plan.
A restated plan document was submitted to the IRS in January 2017. The restated plan document reflects
all changes reflected in the January 1, 2016 valuation, and also includes the following changes adopted
since January 1, 2016:
• The 2017 – 2019 Collective Bargaining Agreement (“Local 503” Extension Agreement) between the
International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers, AFL-CIO and its Local 503 (“Local 503”) and Orange
and Rockland Utilities, Inc. (“O&R”),
• Changes approved by the Boards for Management Employees on and after June 1, 2017 including
the expansion of the population eligible for the lump sum option,
• Plan amendment to change the pivot year for O&R union and management employees to 2014,
effective January 1, 2018
• Plan amendment effective January 1, 2017 to limit the amount of ATIP recognized by the plan to
36% of the participant’s annual base salary rate as of the December 31 prior to the year in which the
award is paid which was first measured as of January 1, 2018 (this amendment had no impact).
The valuation reflects the following changes adopted since January 1, 2019.
• The 2019 collective bargaining contract between Local 503 and O&R gave Local 503 participants
hired before January 1, 2010 a choice between remaining in the cash balance formula or receiving
prospective contributions through a defined contribuiton arrangement under the Thrift Plan. The
choice period ran from June 1, 2019 through May 31, 2023.
• Pivot Year will increase from January 1, 2014 to January 1, 2016 effective January 1, 2020
• Effective January 1, 2020, employees who retire between the ages of 60 and 62 will receive an
additional $1,200 monthly supplement until age 62.
• New Lump Sum Option – Union employees who retire on or after January 1, 2020 will have the
opportunity to elect a lump sum pension distribution as a new form of retirement option.
• Plan amendment effective January 1, 2022 to remove any limit on the amount of ATIP recognized by
the plan.
• Pivot Year will increase from January 1, 2016 to January 1, 2019 effective January 1, 2023
• Pivot Year will increase from January 1, 2019 to January 1, 2021 effective January 1, 2024

Summary of Main Plan Provisions for CEI Participants
Plan Provisions
The two Con Edison pension plans were merged together with the O&R Plan effective January 1, 2001
and became The Con Edison Retirement Plan. At the same time, a new cash balance benefit structure
was introduced for Management employees of Con Edison and O&R hired on or after January 1, 2001
and before January 1, 2017 and employees of CED Operating Company, LLC (Lakewood) who did not
transfer directly from Con Edison. A restated plan document was submitted to the IRS in January 2017.
The restated plan document reflects all changes reflected in the January 1, 2016 valuation, and includes
the following changes adopted since January 1, 2016:
• The 2016 – 2020 Collective Bargaining Contract Between Local Union 1-2 of the Utility Workers
Union of America, AFL-CIO and CECONY,
• Changes approved by the Boards for Management Employees on and after January 1, 2017
including the expansion of the population eligible for the lump sum option, and
• Elimination of the Buy-Back Feature for all participants.
The 2016 collective bargaining contract between Local 1-2 and CECONY gives Local 1-2 participants
hired on or after July 1, 2012 and before June 26, 2016 as well as all Local 1-2 participants hired after
June 25, 2016 a choice between the cash balance formula under the Retirement Plan or contributions to
a defined contribution arrangement under the Thrift Plan. The choice period runs until June 25, 2020 for
participants hired before June 26, 2016 and for 60 days after date of hire for participants hired after June
25, 2016.
The 2016 collective bargaining contract between Local 3 and CECONY closed the Plan to employees
hired after June 24, 2017; those hired June 25, 2017 and later participate in the Thrift Plan only.
Definitions
Accredited Service The service used for calculating the amount of a pension benefit.
In general, it is all service as an employee.
Annual Basic Straight-Time The participant's basic straight-time compensation based on
Compensation regular annual rate in the last pay period in each calendar quarter,
up to a maximum of $72,500 (based on $290,000 per year, as
indexed), multiplied by a fraction where the numerator is the
number of months of the participant's service in each quarter and
the denominator is 3.
